dos to you! <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub30.ezboard.com/bthesentinent.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=airrannalee>Airranna Lee</A> at: 4/17/01 1:59:35 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub30.ezboard.com/bthesentinent.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=teynorsax>Teynor Sax</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sentinent Officer</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#333333>(4/17/01 6:05:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: comments on teynors piece of enchanting 101</span><hr size=1> Thanks Airranna, glad you liked it.  :-)<br>
<br>
In response to your comments (this is kinda' long), yes this does happen a lot.  Pullers and peelers often switch targets and don't let the group know, which can cause a lot of trouble.<br>
<br>
 A lot of times a puller will see something bigger than his original target add in on the way to the group, and decide to nail that instead.  When they don't announce this, the enchanter can end up mezzing the new target, thinking it's just another add.  Problem with this is, the puller usually hasn't had a chance to build up much aggro this early in the fight, and when the next blow lands and wakes the critter that was just mezzed, it will often charge the 'chanter.  Not only does this cost mana that the healer has to waste on the enchanter, but it's more time that the original target is still awake and pounding on stuff.<br>
<br>
Another problem is the speed with which adds get to the group.  When you have a Druid or Ranger pulling for instance, they often pull with snare.  While this helps the fight, it means that adds will actually reach the group before the original pull does.  Most people instictively start beating on the stuff that gets to them, no-one likes to stand there and get nailed without fighting back.  This means that the enchanter can't mez that stuff because it's just being woken up (refer to the part about smooshed 'chanters above..heh), then when the original pull gets there, people are on the wrong stuff.  And then of course...everyone realizes this and switches to the original target..usually just as the enchanter mezzes it to try to get SOME semblance of control over the pull.  <sigh><br>
<br>
The biggest thing I can say for pullers, and groupies, is to stick to the original target!  Except for a very few instances, the few seconds it takes the 'chanter to get stuff under control is not going to mean the difference between life and death for the group, and if it does, you probably shouldn't have been there anyway.  The ONLY time ANYONE should switch targets is when the enchanter says so, otherwise you beat on the called target until dead.  :-)<br>
<br>
Stick to your target, let the 'chanter do his job, and your life will be a whole lot easier.  Nothin better than killing one target and having 3 more lined up and waiting peacefully for ya.<br>
<br>
Teynor Sax<br>
41 Enchanter<br>
Proud member of The Sentinent<br>
